hands_on_practices.problem:
A clinical laboratory receives five unlabeled serous fluid specimens from different hospitalized patients, each accompanied by a simultaneously drawn serum sample. The task is to design a decision algorithm that uses fluid-to-serum ratios to identify whether an unknown serous fluid is most consistent with urine leakage into a cavity, bile leakage, chylous effusion, pancreatic secretion leakage, or a non-specific serous effusion. You must choose the algorithm that is most consistent with first principles and well-tested facts regarding the composition of these fluids, and which correctly classifies all five specimens. Use the following base:

- Creatinine concentration is markedly higher in urine than in serum under normal physiology; therefore, a fluid heavily contaminated with urine will have a fluid-to-serum creatinine ratio that substantially exceeds unity.
- Bilirubin concentration is markedly higher in bile than in serum under normal physiology; therefore, a fluid contaminated with bile will have a fluid-to-serum bilirubin ratio that substantially exceeds unity.
- Chyle is lipid-rich lymph containing chylomicrons and high triglyceride; therefore, chylous effusions have high fluid triglyceride and typically exceed the corresponding serum concentration.
- Pancreatic secretions have high amylase activity; therefore, fluids receiving pancreatic juice will have a fluid-to-serum amylase ratio that substantially exceeds unity.
- Define the fluid-to-serum ratio for an analyte $x$ as $R_{x} = \dfrac{[x]_{\text{fluid}}}{[x]_{\text{serum}}}$.

All concentrations and activities are measured on the same day. Amylase activity is reported in International Units (IU).

Specimen data are shown below (each line lists fluid first, then serum):

- Specimen $1$: Creatinine $8.0$ mg/dL vs $1.0$ mg/dL; Bilirubin $0.6$ mg/dL vs $1.2$ mg/dL; Triglyceride $60$ mg/dL vs $150$ mg/dL; Amylase $200$ IU/L vs $90$ IU/L.
- Specimen $2$: Creatinine $1.2$ mg/dL vs $1.0$ mg/dL; Bilirubin $8.0$ mg/dL vs $1.2$ mg/dL; Triglyceride $80$ mg/dL vs $100$ mg/dL; Amylase $80$ IU/L vs $90$ IU/L.
- Specimen $3$: Creatinine $0.9$ mg/dL vs $1.0$ mg/dL; Bilirubin $0.7$ mg/dL vs $1.0$ mg/dL; Triglyceride $350$ mg/dL vs $140$ mg/dL; Amylase $70$ IU/L vs $90$ IU/L.
- Specimen $4$: Creatinine $1.0$ mg/dL vs $1.0$ mg/dL; Bilirubin $1.0$ mg/dL vs $1.0$ mg/dL; Triglyceride $100$ mg/dL vs $150$ mg/dL; Amylase $1800$ IU/L vs $90$ IU/L.
- Specimen $5$: Creatinine $1.0$ mg/dL vs $1.0$ mg/dL; Bilirubin $0.8$ mg/dL vs $1.0$ mg/dL; Triglyceride $60$ mg/dL vs $100$ mg/dL; Amylase $90$ IU/L vs $90$ IU/L.

Choose the single best algorithm among the options below. Each option specifies the order of checks and cut-offs. If more than one criterion is met, the algorithm assigns the category at the first satisfied step.

A. Check in this order using ratios and established cut-offs emphasizing specificity:
- Urine leak if $R_{\text{creat}} \ge 2$; 
- Else bile leak if $R_{\text{bili}} \ge 2$;
- Else chylous effusion if fluid triglyceride $\ge 110$ mg/dL and $R_{\text{TG}} \ge 1$;
- Else pancreatic secretion leak if $R_{\text{amyl}} \ge 2$;
- Else non-specific serous effusion.

B. Check in this order using minimal ratio elevation:
- Pancreatic secretion leak if $R_{\text{amyl}}  1$;
- Else chylous effusion if $R_{\text{TG}}  1$;
- Else bile leak if $R_{\text{bili}}  1$;
- Else urine leak if $R_{\text{creat}}  1$;
- Else non-specific serous effusion.

C. Use absolute fluid values only, ignoring serum:
- Urine leak if fluid creatinine $\ge 2$ mg/dL;
- Else bile leak if fluid bilirubin $\ge 3$ mg/dL;
- Else chylous effusion if fluid triglyceride $\ge 110$ mg/dL;
- Else pancreatic secretion leak if fluid amylase $\ge 500$ IU/L;
- Else non-specific serous effusion.

D. Use permissive ratio cut-offs without triglyceride absolute criterion:
- Urine leak if $R_{\text{creat}} \ge 1$;
- Else bile leak if $R_{\text{bili}} \ge 1$;
- Else chylous effusion if $R_{\text{TG}} \ge 0.8$;
- Else pancreatic secretion leak if $R_{\text{amyl}} \ge 1.2$;
- Else non-specific serous effusion.

E. Check in this order with mixed cut-offs:
- Pancreatic secretion leak if $R_{\text{amyl}} \ge 2$;
- Else chylous effusion if fluid triglyceride $\ge 110$ mg/dL (regardless of $R_{\text{TG}}$);
- Else urine leak if $R_{\text{creat}} \ge 2$;
- Else bile leak if $R_{\text{bili}} \ge 2$;
- Else non-specific serous effusion.

Which option is best?
